{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic| name=Flagrate| type=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic#Spells|Spell]] (Charm)| features=Marks a surface| appearance=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Order of the Phoenix|''Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix'']]}}
== Overview ==
'''''Flagrate''''' is used to mark things, such as doors, with a flaming mark of some sort.
== Extended Description ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Beginner Spoiler}}
As they enter the Department of Mysteries at the Ministry of Magic, [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Harry Potter|Harry]] and his companions find themselves in an antechamber with a number of identical doors, that seem to spin around every time a door is closed. As a result, it is impossible to tell which doors have already been tried. [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Hermione Granger|Hermione]] uses this spell to mark each door they try, until they find the correct one.
== Analysis ==
Despite the similarity in names, this spell seems to be not particularly similar to the [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Flagrante|Flagrante]] curse.
Presumably this is the spell that [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Rubeus Hagrid|Hagrid]] used when visiting the Dursleys at the Hut on the Rock.
== Questions == {{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Questions}}
== Greater Picture ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Intermediate Spoiler}}
[[Category:Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter]]

{{earthquakes header}}

According to [http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/earthquake Wiktionary], an earthquake (synonym "quake") is "a shaking of the Earth, caused by volcanic activity or movement around geologic faults" or "a natural disaster." This, indeed, comprehensively covers all written about earthquakes. However, you should learn something about this phenomenon's geography.
Most earthquakes occur along tectonic plate boundaries, although one of the worst earthquakes of all time was in Missouri, in 1811. It was felt even in Washington, D.C.

